#
# .hypatia-ignore — scoped, documented exemptions for the Hypatia scanner.
#
# Format (one entry per line):
#
#     <rule_module>/<rule_type>:<path-fragment>
#     <rule_module>/*:<path-fragment>          (any type in module)
#     <path-fragment>                           (any rule, any module)
#
# Lines starting with `#` are comments. A path-fragment is a substring match
# against the repo-relative file path — narrow your fragments to avoid
# accidentally hiding adjacent findings.
#
# Built-in default exemptions are in lib/hypatia/scanner_suppression.ex; do
# not duplicate them here. This file is for *repo-specific* exemptions that
# carry a stated reason in the comment above each entry.
#
# Inline-allow alternative: for one or two sites, prefer an inline directive
# at the call site:
#
#     # hypatia: allow security_errors/secret_detected -- test fixture
#
# This file is for exemptions that span a whole file or directory.

# ─── Python bench helpers — REVOKED ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# The two scripts/*.py bench helpers were removed and re-implemented in
# Rust (scripts/bench-tools/). The org Python ban is now total with no
# exceptions, so this carve-out is deleted rather than carried.

# ─── 2026-05-26 self-dogfood triage ─────────────────────────────────────
#
# Hypatia scans itself in CI. A subset of findings are not real defects —
# either test fixtures that deliberately contain the pattern under test,
# or non-ReScript files where the ReScript-specific CSA001 rule is a
# straight false positive. Each entry below carries a one-line reason.

# CSA001 is a ReScript code-scanning alert. Test fixture is *supposed* to
# trigger it — verifies the rule catches `getExn` on external functions.
code_safety/CSA001:test/soundness/fixtures/code_safety/getexn_on_external.res

# False positive: Rust file matched by ReScript-only CSA001 rule.
code_safety/CSA001:clients/rust/hypatia-client/src/ffi.rs

# False positive: CSA001 fires on .gitignore patterns. Not ReScript code.
code_safety/CSA001:.gitignore
structural_drift/SD013:.gitignore

# CSA002 is a meta-finding ("94 open code-scanning alerts") flagged at the
# repo level. Alert backlog triage is tracked separately, not via this
# scanner — exempt the meta-finding to avoid recursive self-flagging.
code_scanning_alerts/CSA002:hyperpolymath/hypatia

# Test simulation infrastructure: ci_simulation/scenarios.rs and
# assertions.rs are deliberately-panicking test scenarios — `.unwrap()` /
# `.expect()` failures here surface broken fixtures, not runtime DoS.
# 94 unwrap + 8 expect sites in scenarios.rs are by design; treating them
# as production safety violations confuses the signal.
code_safety/unwrap_without_check:integration/src/ci_simulation/scenarios.rs
code_safety/expect_in_hot_path:integration/src/ci_simulation/scenarios.rs
code_safety/expect_in_hot_path:integration/src/ci_simulation/assertions.rs

# fixer/src/scanner.rs uses `.expect("...is a compile-time bug")` on
# regex constants. These regexes parse at module load with infallible
# inputs; the expect is the standard Rust idiom for "this can't fail
# unless the source compiled wrong" and the message already states the
# invariant. The rule sees only the lexical `.expect(` pattern.
code_safety/expect_in_hot_path:fixer/src/scanner.rs

# The Nickel k9 metadata config REFERENCES "Dockerfile" in its
# banned_files list — i.e. the config is declaring that Dockerfiles are
# NOT permitted. The ncl_docker_not_podman rule is matching the lexical
# "docker" string and flagging the policy itself; this is recursive
# self-flagging.
code_safety/ncl_docker_not_podman:.machine_readable/svc/k9/hypatia-metadata.k9.ncl
